1
00:00:05,480 --> 00:00:10,480
Fast. At the beginning of the seventies. That just disappeared later.

2
00:00:10,480 --> 00:00:14,082
As I said, when I was in the military

3
00:00:14,082 --> 00:00:19,082
I found out that I wasn't even allowed to become a non-commissioned officer.

4
00:00:19,082 --> 00:00:24,082
Unless it was for bravery in the face of the enemy. Why? Because of what?

5
00:00:24,082 --> 00:00:29,082
Because of my, uh-uh-uh, because I was a so-called quarter Jew.

6
00:00:29,082 --> 00:00:34,082
And how did you feel when you heard that? Uh, as a second-class person.

7
00:00:34,082 --> 00:00:34,958
Basically

8
00:00:34,958 --> 00:00:39,958
it took me years after the war to get rid of these feelings of inferiority that it gave me.

9
00:00:39,958 --> 00:00:44,958
And a lot of my activities later on were basically an attempt to prove that I could achieve something after all and that I wasn't inferior

10
00:00:44,958 --> 00:00:49,958
as people tried to make me believe at the time. Mhm.

11
00:00:49,958 --> 00:00:54,958
And how did you overcome that? How did I overcome that? Yes.

12
00:00:54,958 --> 00:00:59,958
That's not so easy to answer. It grew-- I gradually grew out of it-- Mhm.

13
00:00:59,958 --> 00:01:04,958
-Later I felt that I was accepted by others and that I could achieve and do something.

14
00:01:04,958 --> 00:01:09,958
Hm, hm. And back then you spoke to your mother and your brother.

15
00:01:09,958 --> 00:01:14,958
Are we inferior - are we inferior? Is this ideology, is it the truth?

16
00:01:14,958 --> 00:01:16,030
Wh-- How...

17
00:01:16,030 --> 00:01:21,030
Were you very influenced by this new ideology, racial science and so on?

18
00:01:21,030 --> 00:01:25,801
Uh, in terms of racial studies, I was against, uh

19
00:01:25,801 --> 00:01:30,801
what was said in the Third Reich right from the start. Mhm.

20
00:01:30,801 --> 00:01:35,801
But, uh, these military successes, that's what impressed me as a boy, uh, uh.

21
00:01:35,801 --> 00:01:36,190
Mhm.

22
00:01:36,190 --> 00:01:41,190
And the, uh, conversations with my parents were always such that they were, uh, against the Nazis.

23
00:01:41,190 --> 00:01:44,014
And so were my brother and I.

24
00:01:44,014 --> 00:01:49,014
But of course we weren't allowed to let them notice us.

25
00:01:49,014 --> 00:01:54,014
Nevertheless, as I said, we weren't completely uninfluenced.

26
00:01:54,014 --> 00:01:58,006
We were in an intermediate position. Mmm.

27
00:01:58,006 --> 00:02:02,582
We were still too young to see through it. Mhm.

28
00:02:02,582 --> 00:02:06,282
I was seventeen at the end of the war.

29
00:02:06,282 --> 00:02:11,282
I didn't have my eighteenth birthday until I was an American prisoner of war

30
00:02:11,282 --> 00:02:16,282
and then I was released at the beginning of forty-six, as an eighteen-year-old.

31
00:02:16,282 --> 00:02:20,177
Why didn't you try to forge your papers?

32
00:02:20,177 --> 00:02:24,169
Why didn't your mother actually try that?

33
00:02:24,169 --> 00:02:29,169
Uh, because my grandfather was very well known and respected as a doctor in Karlsruhe.

34
00:02:29,169 --> 00:02:34,169
And because it was known that he was Jewish, she would have had no chance of forging it.

35
00:02:34,169 --> 00:02:39,169
I know about, uh, this father, this Melitta, um, they obviously managed to keep it secret.

36
00:02:39,169 --> 00:02:44,169
Apparently none of these five, uh, siblings knew that the father was Jewish.

37
00:02:44,169 --> 00:02:49,169
Hmm. But with your case, that was quite different. Yes.

38
00:02:49,169 --> 00:02:53,259
And so in the military, at the draft. Yes.

39
00:02:53,259 --> 00:02:58,259
Did you have to declare that you weren't pure Aryan? No.

40
00:02:58,259 --> 00:03:03,259
So how did that come out? How did people find out about it?

41
00:03:03,259 --> 00:03:07,640
And was the camaraderie in the military good?

42
00:03:07,640 --> 00:03:12,640
Uh, that's actually one of the most valuable things I experienced in human terms back then.

43
00:03:12,640 --> 00:03:16,924
You get to know people. (laughs softly) Mhm.

44
00:03:16,924 --> 00:03:21,924
You see who can't be influenced by something like that and who takes you seriously as a person and comrade (clears throat).

45
00:03:21,924 --> 00:03:22,314
Mhm.

46
00:03:22,314 --> 00:03:27,314
And others who behaved more or less contemptuously or who withdrew because they thought

47
00:03:27,314 --> 00:03:32,314
uh, if I have closer contact with him, it could harm me.

48
00:03:32,314 --> 00:03:37,314
My parents often told me about old acquaintances who, uh, in 1933

49
00:03:37,314 --> 00:03:39,651
from one day to the next

50
00:03:39,651 --> 00:03:44,651
no longer greeted them on the street or no longer knew them.

51
00:03:44,651 --> 00:03:49,651
And, uh, I grew up with this knowledge back then and also experienced it myself

52
00:03:49,651 --> 00:03:54,227
because some people withdrew and others didn't.

53
00:03:54,227 --> 00:03:58,609
But at least I experienced one positive case.

54
00:03:58,609 --> 00:04:03,609
It was during the war when a teacher, who now knew, er

55
00:04:03,609 --> 00:04:08,609
that my grandfather was Jewish, said to my brother and me: "Go outside

56
00:04:08,609 --> 00:04:13,609
I want to talk to the class." And then he, he was a party member

57
00:04:13,609 --> 00:04:18,609
but he wasn't on the inside, he was only on the outside.

58
00:04:18,609 --> 00:04:23,609
And then he took the class and said: "What can they do about it?

59
00:04:23,609 --> 00:04:28,609
Take them in, let them be comrades, just like you." I gave the man a lot of credit for that.

60
00:04:28,609 --> 00:04:33,609
And did your, yes, student comrades actually do that?

61
00:04:33,609 --> 00:04:38,477
One of them objected at the time. And, uh, they...

62
00:04:38,477 --> 00:04:43,477
We noticed that, uh, not all of them, but some of them did behave a bit, uh

63
00:04:43,477 --> 00:04:46,009
more comradely towards us.

64
00:04:46,009 --> 00:04:51,009
But through what, yes, through a what member, you say, right? Yes.

65
00:04:51,009 --> 00:04:56,009
That actually gave you the feeling, didn't it? Still pity, sorry.

66
00:04:56,009 --> 00:05:01,009
Through pity, you would say, wouldn't you? Because they were ordered, actually.

67
00:05:01,009 --> 00:05:06,009
Yes, yes, yes. But there was still a certain restraint.

68
00:05:06,009 --> 00:05:11,009
People were no longer aggressive when I said that, some others were nevertheless, but passive.

69
00:05:11,009 --> 00:05:16,009
But as I said, a few who did were completely impartial and friendly.

70
00:05:16,009 --> 00:05:19,027
And you really appreciate that.

71
00:05:19,027 --> 00:05:24,027
When Hitler came to the market, what did your parents tell you later about this

72
00:05:24,027 --> 00:05:29,027
yes, grasp of the market? Were your parents, were you very influenced by it?

73
00:05:29,027 --> 00:05:31,948
Were you influenced by Hitler?

74
00:05:31,948 --> 00:05:36,948
Did you think that Hitler was our man for the future?

75
00:05:36,948 --> 00:05:41,948
My mother was strongly opposed from the beginning until the end.

76
00:05:41,948 --> 00:05:46,948
My father, like many men of that generation, was probably a bit more nationalistic.

77
00:05:46,948 --> 00:05:51,948
Not in a partisan sense, but that which is German is good and right

78
00:05:51,948 --> 00:05:56,948
roughly in terms of this attitude. And that's why he had a different attitude

79
00:05:56,948 --> 00:06:01,948
even though he was well aware of all the terrible things that were going on.

80
00:06:01,948 --> 00:06:06,948
But there were areas where he also admired the fact that unemployment was getting better

81
00:06:06,948 --> 00:06:11,948
for example, that France was overrun so quickly in the French campaign.

82
00:06:11,948 --> 00:06:16,948
That made him happy at the time. But what about the boys, yes? Yes.

83
00:06:16,948 --> 00:06:19,188
His boys too? Yes, yes.

84
00:06:19,188 --> 00:06:24,188
I was also influenced by this back then and I was happy too.

85
00:06:24,188 --> 00:06:29,188
Did anyone try to persuade your father to perhaps divorce his wife or leave his wife because of his Jewish ancestry?

86
00:06:29,188 --> 00:06:34,188
I don't know about that. That was me... I don't know.

87
00:06:34,188 --> 00:06:38,180
My father and mother had a good marriage.

88
00:06:38,180 --> 00:06:43,180
I don't think they ever thought of anything like that.

89
00:06:43,180 --> 00:06:47,951
I only found out later that if my mother had died

90
00:06:47,951 --> 00:06:52,951
she wouldn't have been allowed to be buried in the usual cemetery because she was half-Jewish.

91
00:06:52,951 --> 00:06:57,917
I don't know where she would have had to be buried.

92
00:06:57,917 --> 00:07:02,917
There was obviously a decree at the time that forbade that.

93
00:07:02,917 --> 00:07:07,917
And was it just you and your brothers who were so-called Mischlinge in that class?

94
00:07:07,917 --> 00:07:12,917
Did you get to know any other so-called half-breeds? Not in my class.

95
00:07:12,917 --> 00:07:17,917
I did have one classmate in elementary school who was Jewish.

96
00:07:17,917 --> 00:07:22,917
They then emigrated. A half-Jew, also a so-called half-Jew.

97
00:07:22,917 --> 00:07:27,785
And later at grammar school we were the only ones.

98
00:07:27,785 --> 00:07:32,361
I only remember one who was one class below me.

99
00:07:32,361 --> 00:07:37,361
He had to leave grammar school in the early forties.

100
00:07:37,361 --> 00:07:42,361
He was half, yes, to whom a brother and I were a quarter. What was his name?

101
00:07:42,361 --> 00:07:47,361
Klaus Hermann, Dr. Klaus Hermann. He was a lawyer and, uh, came after the war

102
00:07:47,361 --> 00:07:52,361
took the entrance exam for my class and we did our A-levels together.

103
00:07:52,361 --> 00:07:57,132
I think he was also in Theresienstadt. And, well.

104
00:07:57,132 --> 00:08:02,132
Can you quickly retell this story about your aunt and this Aryanization?

105
00:08:02,132 --> 00:08:04,761
It's very interesting. Yes.

106
00:08:04,761 --> 00:08:09,761
And when did you - can you say when you found out about it?

107
00:08:09,761 --> 00:08:14,761
I learned about it during the war. Okay. My mother's sister. What was her name?

108
00:08:14,761 --> 00:08:17,488
Renate Schiller at the time.

109
00:08:17,488 --> 00:08:22,488
Um, she worked as a nurse during the war and was with a man who gave her a daughter.

110
00:08:22,488 --> 00:08:27,488
The man was deployed on the Eastern Front. What was his name? Ludwig Eitel.

111
00:08:27,488 --> 00:08:32,488
The marriage was subsequently declared as a marriage.

112
00:08:32,488 --> 00:08:37,488
That was possible at the time. Because he was a senior officer, wasn't he?

113
00:08:37,488 --> 00:08:42,488
He was a captain. Captain. He was then reported missing.

114
00:08:42,488 --> 00:08:47,488
We never heard anything more about him, assuming that he was killed back then

115
00:08:47,488 --> 00:08:52,488
I think it was in '42. And now her name was Renate Eitel.

116
00:08:52,488 --> 00:08:57,488
And a woman worked with her as a sister who was married to a high-ranking National Socialist

117
00:08:57,488 --> 00:09:02,488
which my aunt didn't know at the time. Do you know the names of the sons there?

118
00:09:02,488 --> 00:09:05,896
No, no, unfortunately I don't know.

119
00:09:05,896 --> 00:09:10,896
And she obviously applied for my aunt to be made an honorary Aryan without my aunt's knowledge.

120
00:09:10,896 --> 00:09:14,401
Without, uh, your aunt's child, yes?

121
00:09:14,401 --> 00:09:19,401
Yes, that automatically means the child too, because if she's an honorary Aryan

122
00:09:19,401 --> 00:09:21,543
then the child is too.

123
00:09:21,543 --> 00:09:26,543
And was, um, she pregnant then or had you already had the child?

124
00:09:26,543 --> 00:09:31,543
The child had already been born and, uh, a few weeks later to her great surprise

125
00:09:31,543 --> 00:09:36,543
my aunt received a certificate in which she was named an honorary Aryan.

126
00:09:36,543 --> 00:09:41,543
Uh, about eight days later she was summoned to the Gestapo because she had been denounced.

127
00:09:41,543 --> 00:09:45,048
She was in trouble from an institute

128
00:09:45,048 --> 00:09:50,048
I think it was a housing distribution office or something like that. Mhm.

129
00:09:50,048 --> 00:09:54,527
Uh, she called these people a corrupt society.

130
00:09:54,527 --> 00:09:59,006
And that's why she was summoned to the Gestapo

131
00:09:59,006 --> 00:10:04,006
but she took this certificate of honor with her as a precaution. Mhm.

132
00:10:04,006 --> 00:10:08,388
When she was in the office and was questioned

133
00:10:08,388 --> 00:10:12,867
she showed this honorary officer's certificate

134
00:10:12,867 --> 00:10:17,867
whereupon the Gestapo officer showed her a certificate stating that she had been sent to a concentration camp and then tore it up.

135
00:10:17,867 --> 00:10:22,443
So this certificate practically saved her life.

136
00:10:22,443 --> 00:10:27,443
And when you found out about this Aryanization, what did you think about it?

137
00:10:27,443 --> 00:10:32,443
I was speechless. I didn't even think it was possible that such a thing existed.

138
00:10:32,443 --> 00:10:37,443
But I thought, good for her. You did - it's a shame we don't have it.

139
00:10:37,443 --> 00:10:42,443
Did you try to get that too? Because that was the sister. Yes. Yours-- Yes.

140
00:10:42,443 --> 00:10:43,417
My mother.

141
00:10:43,417 --> 00:10:48,417
My mother obviously, obviously hadn't done anything, so we were left in the same state as before.

142
00:10:48,417 --> 00:10:52,993
But did that give you a bit of hope or not? No.

143
00:10:52,993 --> 00:10:57,993
Did you think that was a one-off, or? We suspected that it must be very rare.

144
00:10:57,993 --> 00:11:02,569
Mmm. We'd never heard of it before and also, er

145
00:11:02,569 --> 00:11:07,569
only found out later in the post-war period that there were exceptional cases.

146
00:11:07,569 --> 00:11:07,959
Mhm.

147
00:11:07,959 --> 00:11:12,959
For example, when I was a prisoner of war, I heard that Field Marshal Milch was a half-breed.

148
00:11:12,959 --> 00:11:17,959
But that was the first case I, uh, heard about, apart from my own aunt. Hm.

149
00:11:17,959 --> 00:11:21,269
Back to her military service. Yes.

150
00:11:21,269 --> 00:11:26,269
When you were given a Wehrmacht uniform and you used it. Yes.

151
00:11:26,269 --> 00:11:31,269
What did you think? I didn't have any particular thoughts.

152
00:11:31,269 --> 00:11:36,269
I was aware that I was one of millions of others. I, uh- Did that help you?

153
00:11:36,269 --> 00:11:41,269
Consciously, I mean. It was a bit of a protection. Mhm.

154
00:11:41,269 --> 00:11:46,269
Uh, a protection, uh, not, uh, being able to be arrested so easily

155
00:11:46,269 --> 00:11:51,138
since I now represent the state myself in uniform.

156
00:11:51,138 --> 00:11:56,138
That's how I felt at the time. Mhm. Was that really the case? Mm.

157
00:11:56,138 --> 00:12:00,909
And was your brother in the same company? No, no.

158
00:12:00,909 --> 00:12:05,909
I was in the pioneers, armored engineers. He joined the artillery.

159
00:12:05,909 --> 00:12:10,909
And was his experience like your experience? Was he, uh...

160
00:12:10,909 --> 00:12:14,122
I suppose more or less, yes. Mmm.

161
00:12:14,122 --> 00:12:19,122
Everyone feels differently, of course, but roughly the same.

162
00:12:19,122 --> 00:12:23,504
For example, when there were fights at school

163
00:12:23,504 --> 00:12:28,504
because someone thought he had to beat me up if possible.

164
00:12:28,504 --> 00:12:33,504
Then he always came to my aid, right. And, uh, so we had a sense of cohesion.

165
00:12:33,504 --> 00:12:38,504
Mhm. And what did your comrades say they were fighting for?

166
00:12:38,504 --> 00:12:43,504
What did they fight for, yes? What reason did you give for that?

167
00:12:43,504 --> 00:12:48,504
Uh, the comrades said very little. That was the official propaganda

168
00:12:48,504 --> 00:12:53,504
which claimed that they were defending Greater Germany against this and that.

169
00:12:53,504 --> 00:12:58,504
Uh, that, uh, I actually, as soon as I became more aware, uh

170
00:12:58,504 --> 00:13:03,504
was able to think for myself in puberty, it was clear to me that that was, uh

171
00:13:03,504 --> 00:13:07,204
propaganda, exaggeration and nonsense.

172
00:13:07,204 --> 00:13:12,204
Uh, I was actually already aware during the French campaign

173
00:13:12,204 --> 00:13:17,204
when they occupied Belgium and Holland, later Norway, uh

174
00:13:17,204 --> 00:13:22,204
and then later other countries, that they hadn't done anything to us.

175
00:13:22,204 --> 00:13:27,204
Why do you-- why do you do that? Or even the declaration of war on America.

176
00:13:27,204 --> 00:13:30,709
What chance do we have against that?

177
00:13:30,709 --> 00:13:35,709
Of course I didn't tell anyone that, but I was already aware of how things were going.

178
00:13:35,709 --> 00:13:40,709
And did your comrades feel like fighting? Some of them, yes. Hm.

179
00:13:40,709 --> 00:13:45,709
And did you, yes, as a child, let's say, did you hope that Germany would win the war?

180
00:13:45,709 --> 00:13:50,709
When I was young, at the beginning of the war, still more of a child, not yet an adolescent.

181
00:13:50,709 --> 00:13:55,709
Back then, yes. But I mean in the military. No, no. For God's sake, no.

182
00:13:55,709 --> 00:14:00,709
There is-- I also remember that once an officer, uh, who probably belonged to a propaganda unit.

183
00:14:00,709 --> 00:14:05,709
He gave lectures like that and the company was seconded and he spoke very suggestively and also talked about the final victory and the secret weapons and all that and then asked them how comradely they were.

184
00:14:05,709 --> 00:14:10,709
Now everyone should say honestly whether they believe that this victory is not...

185
00:14:10,709 --> 00:14:15,709
That this war could no longer be won. And not a single person came forward.

186
00:14:15,709 --> 00:14:20,709
But I still remember feeling guilty because I didn't believe it and was too cowardly to say it.

187
00:14:20,709 --> 00:14:25,709
That's how I thought at the time. Today I'm glad it was like that. Hm. Yes.

188
00:14:25,709 --> 00:14:30,709
Please. Didn't you once say that you were happy when the flak hit? Yes.

189
00:14:30,709 --> 00:14:35,709
That's right. Right? We were deployed as air force helpers. I was in a...

190
00:14:35,709 --> 00:14:40,709
First in a ten-point-five-centimeter battery, later in an eight-point-eight-centimeter battery.

191
00:14:40,709 --> 00:14:45,709
And there were the, um, American or English squadrons, when they moved over us and then...

192
00:14:45,709 --> 00:14:50,709
The planes were shot at. We also saw planes crash several times.

193
00:14:50,709 --> 00:14:55,709
And I saw that, uh, together with my comrades, as a success.

194
00:14:55,709 --> 00:15:00,709
And I was-- Because I also saw that, uh, these airplane attacks, uh

195
00:15:00,709 --> 00:15:05,709
caused a lot of damage in Karlsruhe and other cities

196
00:15:05,709 --> 00:15:10,709
and usually not to military objects, but to civilian buildings.

197
00:15:10,709 --> 00:15:15,709
And how many planes did you shoot down? Or rather, the battery I was in.

198
00:15:15,709 --> 00:15:20,709
Uh, officially, I think we were credited with two or three kills at the time.

199
00:15:20,709 --> 00:15:25,709
But you know, I was able to observe that at the time. Uh

200
00:15:25,709 --> 00:15:30,709
it depended a lot on which company commander was able to present the matter to the regimental commander as if it had been his battery.

201
00:15:30,709 --> 00:15:31,585
As a rule

202
00:15:31,585 --> 00:15:36,585
there were always several batteries firing afterwards and it was never possible to determine exactly what caused the plane to crash.

203
00:15:36,585 --> 00:15:41,585
I was also lucky enough not to be at the cannon myself, but in the so-called defense tower.

204
00:15:41,585 --> 00:15:46,585
This was a section that was only deployed if the optical measuring device failed and the radio measuring device failed or vice versa.

205
00:15:46,585 --> 00:15:51,585
Then we had to pass on certain numbers and I never had to do that

206
00:15:51,585 --> 00:15:56,585
so I personally, uh, wasn't directly involved in the killing of another person.

207
00:15:56,585 --> 00:16:01,585
Not even later in the military. And today that's a...

208
00:16:01,585 --> 00:16:04,604
I'm very glad about that today.

209
00:16:04,604 --> 00:16:09,604
Was your father, uh, your brother, was he in combat? For one, uh, two days.

210
00:16:09,604 --> 00:16:12,427
And what did he say about it?

211
00:16:12,427 --> 00:16:17,427
Uh, that they were heavily shot at, that comrades fell next to them.

212
00:16:17,427 --> 00:16:21,419
I don't know myself whether he fired too.

213
00:16:21,419 --> 00:16:26,419
In any case, he was then taken prisoner. He was in the West, yes?

214
00:16:26,419 --> 00:16:31,419
He was captured near Heilbronn and I was captured in Ulm.

215
00:16:31,419 --> 00:16:34,633
Okay, so with the Americans. Yes.

216
00:16:34,633 --> 00:16:39,209
When did you find out about, uh, the Holocaust?

217
00:16:39,209 --> 00:16:44,209
I found out about concentration camps relatively early on.

218
00:16:44,209 --> 00:16:49,209
Uh, around 1942 or '43, I heard other people tell me, uh

219
00:16:49,209 --> 00:16:54,209
that SS people had come on vacation who were in a very bad way and who had said that the concentration camps they were in were horrible.

220
00:16:54,209 --> 00:16:59,209
But they weren't allowed to say anything because then they themselves might be

221
00:16:59,209 --> 00:17:01,448
uh, sentenced to death.

222
00:17:01,448 --> 00:17:06,448
But it was so horrible that you couldn't say anything about it.

223
00:17:06,448 --> 00:17:11,448
And that's when I began to realize that the Jews, who everyone knew would one day be gone.

224
00:17:11,448 --> 00:17:16,448
And not just the emigrants, we knew that they had left

225
00:17:16,448 --> 00:17:21,448
but that the others who had been sent to camps were not only doing very badly

226
00:17:21,448 --> 00:17:26,448
but it seemed likely to me at the time that these people had also been killed.

227
00:17:26,448 --> 00:17:31,448
I didn't know any more details, but I assume that if I

228
00:17:31,448 --> 00:17:36,448
as a fourteen-year-old or fifteen-year-old, heard that at the time

229
00:17:36,448 --> 00:17:40,441
then other people must have heard it too.

230
00:17:40,441 --> 00:17:45,441
So if they kept saying later: "Yes, I have no idea." These people

231
00:17:45,441 --> 00:17:49,433
they repressed it or they don't admit it.

232
00:17:49,433 --> 00:17:54,398
And, uh, also the threats with concentration camps.

233
00:17:54,398 --> 00:17:59,398
You didn't hear the name Auschwitz, but Dachau, for example

234
00:17:59,398 --> 00:18:04,398
was a well-known concentration camp whose name was heard more often.

235
00:18:04,398 --> 00:18:09,267
And, uh, in captivity... After the first few weeks

236
00:18:09,267 --> 00:18:14,267
after I came from the collection camp to a labor camp, that's when, uh

237
00:18:14,267 --> 00:18:17,967
we prisoners of war also became known.

238
00:18:17,967 --> 00:18:22,967
And then I was also astonished that it had been carried out on such a huge scale

239
00:18:22,967 --> 00:18:27,641
that millions of people had been killed, and, uh

240
00:18:27,641 --> 00:18:32,641
at that time more than half of my German comrades dismissed it as American propaganda and said: "That can't be true." Hm.

241
00:18:32,641 --> 00:18:37,641
And after the war, did you ever feel guilty about what you did at the, at the flat, right?

242
00:18:37,641 --> 00:18:42,641
No, uh, not that. I, uh, I didn't see the big picture back then.

243
00:18:42,641 --> 00:18:47,641
I wasn't ashamed of it. I was ashamed of something else, though.

244
00:18:47,641 --> 00:18:52,641
I wasn't just in an anti-aircraft battery, but later also in the Stab regiment

245
00:18:52,641 --> 00:18:57,641
and they also had Russian prisoners of war as auxiliaries. Mhm.

246
00:18:57,641 --> 00:19:02,641
And one of these Russian auxiliaries once offered me a job in arts and crafts if I could give him bread in return.

247
00:19:02,641 --> 00:19:07,641
And I didn't do it and I'm still ashamed of that today.

248
00:19:07,641 --> 00:19:12,641
And during that time, did you lose any Jewish relatives in the Holocaust? No.

249
00:19:12,641 --> 00:19:17,412
Hm. And with your aunt- Hai--, you knew that this

250
00:19:17,412 --> 00:19:22,412
this Aryanization was her salvation from the concentration camp man? Yes.

251
00:19:22,412 --> 00:19:27,412
The Gestapo. Yes. Were you afraid for yourself that you would also be deported?

252
00:19:27,412 --> 00:19:32,412
Uh, I was afraid that something might happen to me, but I didn't realize how it might happen.

253
00:19:32,412 --> 00:19:35,333
Mhm. And about those Russians.

254
00:19:35,333 --> 00:19:40,201
Why didn't you feel more, yes, compassion for him?

255
00:19:40,201 --> 00:19:45,201
Were you afraid to help him, were you? A little, yes. For what?

256
00:19:45,201 --> 00:19:50,201
Was it forbidden? Yes. Forbidden to do that? Yes, that was forbidden. Hm.

257
00:19:50,201 --> 00:19:55,201
And how did he react when you said, "No." He withdrew. He had no other choice.

258
00:19:55,201 --> 00:20:00,201
Hmm. And why did this event, why did it, uh, make such a deep impression on you?

259
00:20:00,201 --> 00:20:05,201
Because I realized that the situation itself, uh, made me react inhumanely. Hm.

260
00:20:05,201 --> 00:20:10,201
Is it your fault or is it the society you grew up in, uh.

261
00:20:10,201 --> 00:20:15,201
Especially with this Nazi propaganda, is that to blame?

262
00:20:15,201 --> 00:20:20,201
I don't just want to blame others. It's always yourself as well.

263
00:20:20,201 --> 00:20:25,201
Of course they were the cause, but I mean, I could have reacted differently.

264
00:20:25,201 --> 00:20:25,591
Mmm.

265
00:20:25,591 --> 00:20:30,591
Did your mother find it strange that you and your brother had to serve in the German Wehrmacht as so-called half-breeds?

266
00:20:30,591 --> 00:20:35,591
Yes. Hm. And did you talk to your mother about it? I can't remember.

267
00:20:35,591 --> 00:20:38,901
What good would it have done? Mhm.

268
00:20:38,901 --> 00:20:43,901
It would have, it would have turned out the way it was supposed to.

269
00:20:43,901 --> 00:20:48,901
We would have had to report to the military, we would have gone. Mhm.

270
00:20:48,901 --> 00:20:53,901
And your mother, were you afraid of being deported? I think so, yes.

271
00:20:53,901 --> 00:20:57,698
She hoped that she would be spared that

272
00:20:57,698 --> 00:21:02,698
because my father was severely war-damaged from the First World War

273
00:21:02,698 --> 00:21:06,399
fifty percent, he was hard of hearing.

274
00:21:06,399 --> 00:21:11,399
And it could be that, uh, that the reason was that nothing happened to her.

275
00:21:11,399 --> 00:21:16,170
Uh, I suspect that if that had gone on any longer

276
00:21:16,170 --> 00:21:21,135
all the half-Jews might have been deported as well.

277
00:21:21,135 --> 00:21:25,712
She was lucky that nothing happened to her. Hm.

278
00:21:25,712 --> 00:21:30,712
From all your experiences back then, what have you learned for your life?

279
00:21:30,712 --> 00:21:35,712
Uh, to be tolerant even towards minorities, for example.

280
00:21:35,712 --> 00:21:40,712
Whether it's the Turks today or someone else tomorrow.

281
00:21:40,712 --> 00:21:44,704
Uh, it's, uh, self-evident to me that, uh

282
00:21:44,704 --> 00:21:49,378
no one is inferior to anyone else because of, uh

283
00:21:49,378 --> 00:21:54,378
their origin or religion or anything else. That's completely nonsensical.

284
00:21:54,378 --> 00:21:59,378
Uh-huh. Doctor, thank you. Sir, can you say your name? What is your name?

285
00:21:59,378 --> 00:22:04,378
For my documentation. Heinz Schindler. And where and when were you born?

286
00:22:04,378 --> 00:22:06,812
02.06.13. Mhm. And where?

287
00:22:06,812 --> 00:22:11,812
And when you were young, did you know that you were of Jewish descent?

288
00:22:11,812 --> 00:22:16,812
From the beginning, yes. Hm. Were you brought up in Jewish customs, or? No. Hm.

289
00:22:16,812 --> 00:22:21,812
Because my Jewish father left the Jewish community in Berlin out of political conviction.

290
00:22:21,812 --> 00:22:26,812
Did he give a reason for that? A what? Give a reason for it?

291
00:22:26,812 --> 00:22:31,812
He was a convinced socialist and dissident, as they call it.

292
00:22:31,812 --> 00:22:36,096
Although he came from an orthodox household.

293
00:22:36,096 --> 00:22:41,096
And, uh, did he have trouble with his parents because he married a non-Jewish woman?

294
00:22:41,096 --> 00:22:46,096
Yes. Hm. Yes, very much so. Hm. But he didn't care. Hm. And on the other hand

295
00:22:46,096 --> 00:22:51,096
your mother's parents had difficulties because they- My mother had no, uh

296
00:22:51,096 --> 00:22:56,096
parents who had died very young. My mother grew up with so-called step-parents.

297
00:22:56,096 --> 00:22:59,017
There were no problems at all.

298
00:22:59,017 --> 00:23:04,017
What's more, my mother only met my father when she had long, uh, passed away.

299
00:23:04,017 --> 00:23:09,017
How old was my mother? Uhhh, about twenty-six years old.

300
00:23:09,017 --> 00:23:14,017
So, she was in charge of herself. She wasn't responsible to anyone. Hmmm.

301
00:23:14,017 --> 00:23:19,017
So, how were you brought up in religion? Uhhh, as a dissident. Dissident, yes.

302
00:23:19,017 --> 00:23:22,912
Without any religious affiliation. Hmmm.

303
00:23:22,912 --> 00:23:27,912
The fact that it was different afterwards was a tactical technical move, nothing more.

304
00:23:27,912 --> 00:23:32,912
Hmmm. And did you have contact with your Jewish grandparents?

305
00:23:32,912 --> 00:23:37,912
Yes, not grandparents, but grandmother. Hmmm. Uh, three aunts, two uncles. Hmmm.

306
00:23:37,912 --> 00:23:41,612
And did you go to the synagogue a lot?

307
00:23:41,612 --> 00:23:46,612
But yes, I even sang on the Jewish holidays of Shom Kippur and Rosh Ha-Shanah.

308
00:23:46,612 --> 00:23:50,020
In a liberal synagogue. Sure- Hmmm.

309
00:23:50,020 --> 00:23:55,020
-had to be liberal, because the Orthodox didn't sing in the choir. Hmmm.

310
00:23:55,020 --> 00:24:00,020
And do you still remember your prayers or your songs? But yes. Oh.

311
00:24:00,020 --> 00:24:02,454
Can you, uh, repeat that?

312
00:24:02,454 --> 00:24:07,454
Yes, let's start with Ma Tow or, uh, all, uh Asehle man schmecho.

313
00:24:07,454 --> 00:24:12,454
Anything like that. Do you do that these days? No. (laughs) So, yes.

314
00:24:12,454 --> 00:24:17,454
Can you describe your childhood, uh, to the students?

315
00:24:17,454 --> 00:24:21,057
It was a very normal childhood. Hmmm.

316
00:24:21,057 --> 00:24:26,057
Did you have any difficulties because of your- Not at all.

317
00:24:26,057 --> 00:24:31,057
That didn't exist in my time. Ha. So when the Nazis came to power - yes.

318
00:24:31,057 --> 00:24:36,057
-Did you talk to your parents about what we should do, maybe go abroad, or?

319
00:24:36,057 --> 00:24:40,438
Not at all. That wasn't an issue at all. Hmm.

320
00:24:40,438 --> 00:24:45,438
So, what did you think when Hitler came to power? Yes.

321
00:24:45,438 --> 00:24:50,438
(takes a deep breath) Uh, that was an inevitable fate. Hmm.

322
00:24:50,438 --> 00:24:55,438
Determined by many factors that have long since become common knowledge.

323
00:24:55,438 --> 00:24:58,651
Unemployment, the shaky democracy

324
00:24:58,651 --> 00:25:03,651
the right-wing circles from the old officers around Ludendorff, Hohenberg

325
00:25:03,651 --> 00:25:04,625
Stahlhelm.

326
00:25:04,625 --> 00:25:09,625
That was one side that was constantly working against the Weimar Republic in-- And on the other side

327
00:25:09,625 --> 00:25:14,625
of course, was communism, wasn't it? In 1925, for example, when Ebert died

328
00:25:14,625 --> 00:25:19,625
a new Reich President had to be elected and the entire right-wing coalition

329
00:25:19,625 --> 00:25:24,625
from the German Nationals at the top down to the Center, uh, put up Hindenburg.

330
00:25:24,625 --> 00:25:29,396
And the Social Democrats had their own candidate.

331
00:25:29,396 --> 00:25:34,396
And the worst thing in my view was that the Communists also had their own candidate.

332
00:25:34,396 --> 00:25:37,317
So that means, together- Hmhm.

333
00:25:37,317 --> 00:25:42,317
-Social Democrats and Communists could have easily got their candidate through.

334
00:25:42,317 --> 00:25:47,317
But the fact that the Communists always insisted on representing their own, uh

335
00:25:47,317 --> 00:25:52,317
interests, that was completely wrong and apolitical.

336
00:25:52,317 --> 00:25:55,920
In other words, from my point of view

337
00:25:55,920 --> 00:26:00,920
the Communists were largely to blame for the National Socialists coming to power in 1933.

338
00:26:00,920 --> 00:26:05,920
The fact that they had to pay for it all afterwards is another matter. Hmhm.

339
00:26:05,920 --> 00:26:10,920
Yes, and that's how I grew up and when I wasn't quite so affected by it, I became seriously ill.

340
00:26:10,920 --> 00:26:15,920
In other words, during the transition period I was in hospital with severe kidney poisoning.

341
00:26:15,920 --> 00:26:20,920
And when that had subsided, as I was a musician, I went back to making music on a freelance basis.

342
00:26:20,920 --> 00:26:25,920
Then came the first big blow: I was no longer allowed to pursue my profession as a musician because the so-called Reichsmusikkammer didn't accept me and my brother.

343
00:26:25,920 --> 00:26:30,920
Do you know the encyclopedia Jews in Music? Aha, you see. But I have it.

344
00:26:30,920 --> 00:26:35,920
That means I'm in an encyclopaedia during my lifetime.

345
00:26:35,920 --> 00:26:38,451
Although not very edifying

346
00:26:38,451 --> 00:26:43,451
because this encyclopaedia was only intended for the official use of the NSDAP.

347
00:26:43,451 --> 00:26:48,125
In other words, all the so-called administrators

348
00:26:48,125 --> 00:26:53,125
everyone who had anything to do with music in the so-called Third Reich

349
00:26:53,125 --> 00:26:56,728
had this encyclopaedia on their desk.

350
00:26:56,728 --> 00:27:01,304
And it listed all those who were either Jewish.

351
00:27:01,304 --> 00:27:06,304
Jewish by blood, not the quarter-Jews, they weren't in there.

352
00:27:06,304 --> 00:27:11,304
But composers like Mendelssohn Bartholdy, like Gustav Mahler

353
00:27:11,304 --> 00:27:16,304
conductors like Blech, Bruno Walter Klemperer were all in there.

354
00:27:16,304 --> 00:27:20,199
And I have the honor of being in it too.

355
00:27:20,199 --> 00:27:25,199
I'm proud of that, even though it was directed against me at the time.

356
00:27:25,199 --> 00:27:30,199
So that means that nobody hired me because I was in that dictionary. Yes.

357
00:27:30,199 --> 00:27:34,678
Shall we show him? What's your brother's name?

358
00:27:34,678 --> 00:27:39,678
My brother is deceased, but he's also in the dictionary. Hm. What's his name?

359
00:27:39,678 --> 00:27:40,943
Erwin. Erwin.

360
00:27:40,943 --> 00:27:45,943
That's the one who was in that squad with Wolfgang Behrend, Günter Lebrandt

361
00:27:45,943 --> 00:27:50,943
Werner Gransch, Bosshardt, who weren't in the Wehrmacht

362
00:27:50,943 --> 00:27:55,943
they were in the so-called UT, weren't they? That was a forced labor formation.

363
00:27:55,943 --> 00:28:00,943
And my brother was there. I myself served as the lowest rank in the Wehrmacht.

364
00:28:00,943 --> 00:28:05,943
As you can see, that's the success. You can easily get this book in anyone.

365
00:28:05,943 --> 00:28:10,943
What did you say? Which archive are you with? The Federal Archives. Of course.

366
00:28:10,943 --> 00:28:15,943
Do you want to make a note of that? Yes, afterward. Oh, I told you.

367
00:28:15,943 --> 00:28:20,943
Give me that, child. Here you are. This is the lexicon of Jews in music.

368
00:28:20,943 --> 00:28:24,254
Von Stengel crossed out the court.

369
00:28:24,254 --> 00:28:29,254
Those were the two rascals who compiled it with a list of titles of Jewish works on behalf of the Reichsleitung der NSDAP on the basis of official party-approved documents

370
00:28:29,254 --> 00:28:30,520
edited by Dr.

371
00:28:30,520 --> 00:28:35,520
Theo Stengel, consultant at the Reichsmusikkammer in conjunction with Dr. habil.

372
00:28:35,520 --> 00:28:36,786
Herbert Gerig

373
00:28:36,786 --> 00:28:41,786
Head of the Main Office for Music at the Führer's Commissioner for the Supervision of the NSDAP's entire intellectual and ideological training and education.

374
00:28:41,786 --> 00:28:46,786
The worst thing is that these two thugs. After 1945.

375
00:28:46,786 --> 00:28:51,786
in the judicial authority of Lower Saxony. One was a public prosecutor.

376
00:28:51,786 --> 00:28:55,291
I don't know what the other one did.

377
00:28:55,291 --> 00:29:00,291
I once thought I'd go there and murder them or something.

378
00:29:00,291 --> 00:29:03,601
But it wouldn't have been any use.

379
00:29:03,601 --> 00:29:08,601
So they still had well-paid jobs in the so-called republic after 1945.

380
00:29:08,601 --> 00:29:13,601
And now, of course, I'm drawing a parallel with today's Federal Republic.

381
00:29:13,601 --> 00:29:17,399
Politically, it stinks everywhere here.

382
00:29:17,399 --> 00:29:22,399
You have the recent events in the Bundeswehr, the right-wing extremists, the anti-Semites.

383
00:29:22,399 --> 00:29:26,780
That's how it started in the Weimar Republic.

384
00:29:26,780 --> 00:29:31,780
And today we're at that point again. So. What else do you want to know?

385
00:29:31,780 --> 00:29:36,780
So, in 1935, please? In 1935, when the Nuremberg Laws came out. But before that.

386
00:29:36,780 --> 00:29:41,780
I was already at these documents before that. Before 35. That's the nastiness.

387
00:29:41,780 --> 00:29:46,780
But when you were suddenly a so-called half-Jew, in 35, with these new laws

388
00:29:46,780 --> 00:29:51,780
what did you think about it? What was I supposed to think?

389
00:29:51,780 --> 00:29:55,578
I was glad that they didn't pick me up.

390
00:29:55,578 --> 00:30:00,578
And I earned my living doing very menial work in a factory as an unskilled laborer and was glad that they didn't get me.

391
00:30:00,578 --> 00:30:05,578
That worked. You said you were with the Schmechel brother. The...

392
00:30:05,578 --> 00:30:08,012
They were three brothers.

393
00:30:08,012 --> 00:30:13,012
And I worked in a factory until I was nineteen thirty-nine

394
00:30:13,012 --> 00:30:18,012
until the beginning of the Second World War, which produced so-called pills

395
00:30:18,012 --> 00:30:23,012
machines, I don't know, for the whole, uh, what do you call it, Mona?

396
00:30:23,012 --> 00:30:28,012
A pharmacy or- Yes, yes. Well, they make pills, medicines.

397
00:30:28,012 --> 00:30:31,809
I was employed there as a small worker.

398
00:30:31,809 --> 00:30:36,809
And the moment the war started, the authorized signatory

399
00:30:36,809 --> 00:30:41,809
who was actually quite sympathetic to me, called me in and said: "Mr.

400
00:30:41,809 --> 00:30:46,809
Schindler, we have to part company with you, because we're a military company from now on.

401
00:30:46,809 --> 00:30:51,809
We all have to be sworn in and you can't be sworn in." Yes. Then, uh

402
00:30:51,809 --> 00:30:56,809
since there was a shortage of work because so many people had been drafted

403
00:30:56,809 --> 00:31:00,899
I ended up in a machine factory in Moabit.

404
00:31:00,899 --> 00:31:05,899
Since I was already familiar with accounting, payroll accounting and, and, and

405
00:31:05,899 --> 00:31:09,307
and, worker cards and, and, and, um

406
00:31:09,307 --> 00:31:14,307
I got a position there as a post-calculator, as it was called.

407
00:31:14,307 --> 00:31:19,307
And there was one of my, how should I put it, colleagues

408
00:31:19,307 --> 00:31:24,307
he was quite young at the time, standing at the lathe. That was Horst Schmechel.

409
00:31:24,307 --> 00:31:29,307
I've known him since 1940, Horst. He lives in Dortmund. Did you ever visit him?

410
00:31:29,307 --> 00:31:34,307
Mhm. Yes. You were in Dortmund then too? Yes, he was.

411
00:31:34,307 --> 00:31:39,307
Didn't he tell you about me? No. A little bit. Please?

412
00:31:39,307 --> 00:31:44,307
He said a bit-- He said that, uh, you met someone else back then. Yes.

413
00:31:44,307 --> 00:31:49,307
But I was much older than him. He was still an apprentice back then.

414
00:31:49,307 --> 00:31:54,307
(bell ringing) In 1936, I was officially sent to the, uh, Wehrmacht examination

415
00:31:54,307 --> 00:31:59,307
that is, a soldier's examination. I don't know what that shit is called.

416
00:31:59,307 --> 00:32:02,033
Mustering. Mustering, right.

417
00:32:02,033 --> 00:32:07,033
Yes, these things, uh, don't let me articulate properly

418
00:32:07,033 --> 00:32:12,033
because then I always get the coffee up when I think about this crap. Mmm.

419
00:32:12,033 --> 00:32:17,033
So I was drafted in '36 and my kidney disease from 1934 still had an effect.

420
00:32:17,033 --> 00:32:21,317
You know, you have to urinate and, and, and.

421
00:32:21,317 --> 00:32:26,317
And so I still had a very high protein content and was written up as unfit.

422
00:32:26,317 --> 00:32:30,017
Now I have to proceed in the same way.

423
00:32:30,017 --> 00:32:34,886
Uh, nineteen forty-one, end of nineteen forty-one.

424
00:32:34,886 --> 00:32:39,886
I lived in Berlin in Wedding and now comes something that's not so obvious or anything.

425
00:32:39,886 --> 00:32:44,886
When I say, "Yes, why?" A Nazi, a teacher, lived above me and he had a Polish maid.

426
00:32:44,886 --> 00:32:49,886
And he took this oaf of a girl and my mother suffered because of it.

427
00:32:49,886 --> 00:32:54,886
And I listened to it for quite a while and at least I didn't want my mother to...

428
00:32:54,886 --> 00:32:59,559
I don't know anymore. I'm a bit choleric, maybe.

429
00:32:59,559 --> 00:33:04,559
I went up there, banged on the door and made a mess of them, as we say in Germany.

430
00:33:04,559 --> 00:33:09,559
So I shouted, yes, and also insulted them, telling them to leave my mother alone.

