00:49:40,976 --> 00:49:45,976
shocking speech that he and his parliamentary group could not agree to this Enabling Act

644
00:49:45,976 --> 00:49:50,357
this Enabling Act. That speech was appalling.

645
00:49:50,357 --> 00:49:55,357
I don't know what happened to Otto Wels. During your military service.

646
00:49:55,357 --> 00:50:00,357
After you were wounded - yes. Did you continue to serve in the German Wehrmacht?

647
00:50:00,357 --> 00:50:04,934
No. You were discharged? I was discharged, yes.

648
00:50:04,934 --> 00:50:09,934
And did you have a- I told you that. Then I sang in the choir.

649
00:50:09,934 --> 00:50:14,934
So I was discharged. But not in the Wehrmacht choir? No, in the radio choir.

650
00:50:14,934 --> 00:50:19,934
Berlin radio. And then this SS-Sturmbannführer kicked me out.

651
00:50:19,934 --> 00:50:24,934
Did you get special permission because of your serious injury? No. (laughs) Why?

652
00:50:24,934 --> 00:50:27,465
I'm just telling you. Mhm.

653
00:50:27,465 --> 00:50:32,465
The Sturmbannführer said that even if I was severely wounded in the war

654
00:50:32,465 --> 00:50:37,465
even if you were severely, severely wounded in the war

655
00:50:37,465 --> 00:50:42,465
you would remain a Jewish person. Make sure you get out.

656
00:50:42,465 --> 00:50:47,465
But what did the Wehrmacht say? Nothing at all. What should they say?

657
00:50:47,465 --> 00:50:51,165
The Wehrmacht isn't interested at all.

658
00:50:51,165 --> 00:50:56,165
What kind of constitution do you have in mind under "Wehrmacht"?

659
00:50:56,165 --> 00:50:59,476
I didn't even exist for them. Mhm.

660
00:50:59,476 --> 00:51:04,476
Were you allowed to get medals in your company? Honors? Yes.

661
00:51:04,476 --> 00:51:09,476
I was automatically entitled to the silver medal for the wounded and I should have been promoted to private.

662
00:51:09,476 --> 00:51:14,476
Neither happened. The Wehrmacht gave you a reason why? Yes.

663
00:51:14,476 --> 00:51:19,476
It was swept under the table, swept under the carpet.

664
00:51:19,476 --> 00:51:24,476
You can't blame me for being so clear here. No, please.

665
00:51:24,476 --> 00:51:29,476
It always makes my head spin when I think about it. Hm Zuavang is enough.

666
00:51:29,476 --> 00:51:34,476
How are you wounded? What happened? Why don't you talk here?

667
00:51:34,476 --> 00:51:39,476
Yes, but what happened in Russia? In Russia. It was a so-called Ratsch. Boom.

668
00:51:39,476 --> 00:51:41,910
I can't tell myself that.

669
00:51:41,910 --> 00:51:46,910
It's an artillery shell that creaks and scatters at about that height.

670
00:51:46,910 --> 00:51:51,910
And that's how my arm was shot through. And did your comrades help you?

671
00:51:51,910 --> 00:51:56,910
Immediately, yes. Immediately. Oh, I wasn't with the company then.

672
00:51:56,910 --> 00:52:00,805
I was in a medical tent because of lice.

673
00:52:00,805 --> 00:52:04,992
Yes, yes, no, they helped me straight away.

674
00:52:04,992 --> 00:52:09,992
So, you joined a normal company later, with this medic. When later?

675
00:52:09,992 --> 00:52:14,992
After you were wounded? No, you said before I was wounded.

676
00:52:14,992 --> 00:52:19,992
That's when I was relieved of those horrible points on the rifle slope

677
00:52:19,992 --> 00:52:23,302
because I'd had a solitary attack.

678
00:52:23,302 --> 00:52:28,302
And in the army, did your comrades "feel like fighting? What did they have?

679
00:52:28,302 --> 00:52:33,302
A desire to fight. Oh, where from? So what did your comrades fight for?

680
00:52:33,302 --> 00:52:37,392
Well, their lives, because they wanted to.

681
00:52:37,392 --> 00:52:42,392
They weren't interested in what was over there or anywhere else.

682
00:52:42,392 --> 00:52:45,994
They were just fighting for survival.

683
00:52:45,994 --> 00:52:50,994
And did the people under someone else talk about Hitler to the government?

684
00:52:50,994 --> 00:52:55,994
Oh dear, where? No. How were we supposed to talk politics over there?

685
00:52:55,994 --> 00:52:59,694
That would have been completely wrong.

686
00:52:59,694 --> 00:53:03,881
They had to see everyone else as a traitor.

687
00:53:03,881 --> 00:53:08,881
Did you have to swear an oath to Hitler in this preservation battalion? No.

688
00:53:08,881 --> 00:53:13,881
No, I wasn't sworn in. I don't think so. I can't say that for sure now.

689
00:53:13,881 --> 00:53:18,881
I don't think I was sworn in. I don't think so. Or I do.

690
00:53:18,881 --> 00:53:22,386
I know, I can't answer that for you.

691
00:53:22,386 --> 00:53:27,386
But if I had been asked, I would have done so. Of course I would have.

692
00:53:27,386 --> 00:53:32,386
I'm not a hero. Who did you actually hope, apart from the teacher, I think

693
00:53:32,386 --> 00:53:37,386
would get permission to stay in the German Wehrmacht?

694
00:53:37,386 --> 00:53:42,386
That local group leader, I told him just now. And his whole name?

695
00:53:42,386 --> 00:53:47,386
Is he running around? I can't remember his name. No, I don't remember.

696
00:53:47,386 --> 00:53:52,386
But had other people written letters for you? Recommendation letters?

697
00:53:52,386 --> 00:53:57,386
No, no, no, nothing. Did you send photos there? What? Photos of you?

698
00:53:57,386 --> 00:54:02,386
No, not really. So how long did it take you to talk to this leader?

699
00:54:02,386 --> 00:54:07,386
To the group leader, yes. Until you got the authorization. How many weeks?

700
00:54:07,386 --> 00:54:12,386
Four months. Four months. What was your hope for the future during that time?

701
00:54:12,386 --> 00:54:17,386
Did you think that if I didn't have the opportunity, I would leave?

702
00:54:17,386 --> 00:54:22,060
Or did you think I could have a life in Germany?

703
00:54:22,060 --> 00:54:25,955
I just have to survive through this war.

704
00:54:25,955 --> 00:54:30,955
If I hadn't lost this arm, I would have been the first to emigrate to Israel.

705
00:54:30,955 --> 00:54:35,955
I would have emigrated to Israel immediately. So why didn't you do that?

706
00:54:35,955 --> 00:54:40,955
What did I want? With one arm, what was I supposed to do?

707
00:54:40,955 --> 00:54:45,955
They only needed people who could work well in the kibbutz, who could get stuck in.

708
00:54:45,955 --> 00:54:50,955
That's not even a question. Do you feel a strong connection with Israel?

709
00:54:50,955 --> 00:54:55,955
A first cousin was an airplane observer during the Six-Day War and one of my father's brothers

710
00:54:55,955 --> 00:55:00,955
my uncle, who had just come over in 1936, lived in the Dominican Republic

711
00:55:00,955 --> 00:55:05,823
then in Argentina and visited his nephew in Israel

712
00:55:05,823 --> 00:55:10,823
this military airplane observer. And he refused to talk to his uncle in German.

713
00:55:10,823 --> 00:55:15,823
I think that's all right. I think that's very right. Yes.

714
00:55:15,823 --> 00:55:19,913
Have you been to Israel? No, never before.

715
00:55:19,913 --> 00:55:24,913
I have no intention of going there either. That's not a contradiction at all.

716
00:55:24,913 --> 00:55:29,913
I'm also very, very critical of that. Everything that's happening in Israel.

717
00:55:29,913 --> 00:55:34,586
Have they not learned from the 6 million gassed?

718
00:55:34,586 --> 00:55:38,676
I couldn't have foreseen that at the time.

719
00:55:38,676 --> 00:55:43,676
In 1945, who would have believed that this Risches, this Netanyahu

720
00:55:43,676 --> 00:55:48,676
the murdered rabbi, would go off? It's going to blow up. I'm telling you. Why?

721
00:55:48,676 --> 00:55:53,676
After the war, you tried to live in another country, (crosstalk 00:00:09) except Germany.

722
00:55:53,676 --> 00:55:58,676
No, but not as a gravity-damaged person. You must realize that.

723
00:55:58,676 --> 00:56:03,676
Which country is interested in taking in a gravity-damaged person?

724
00:56:03,676 --> 00:56:08,676
Have you tried? But you didn't, you didn't, uh, like living in Germany.

725
00:56:08,676 --> 00:56:13,447
Did you after the Adenauer and Globka, uh, event.

726
00:56:13,447 --> 00:56:18,447
Did you think, maybe, I should go away from this country? No, no.

727
00:56:18,447 --> 00:56:23,447
It didn't go that far. I saw it with contempt. I saw it with disdain

728
00:56:23,447 --> 00:56:28,447
but nobody could take away my relationship to German culture

729
00:56:28,447 --> 00:56:31,271
or above all to German music.

730
00:56:31,271 --> 00:56:36,271
Nobody has taken that away from me and still hasn't.

731
00:56:36,271 --> 00:56:41,271
I still deal with my god, if you like. That is Gustav Mahler.

732
00:56:41,271 --> 00:56:46,271
I was already familiar with Gustav Mahler's symphonies when Gustav Mahler wasn't even a household name.

733
00:56:46,271 --> 00:56:49,971
Today you hear, ahem, that's en vogue.

734
00:56:49,971 --> 00:56:54,971
I had my first encounter with Gustav Mahler in 1930, with the, uh

735
00:56:54,971 --> 00:56:59,971
first symphony, with the Titan, when I was at college. Mmm.

736
00:56:59,971 --> 00:57:04,971
So, now you know so much about me. And what did you play? I was a clarinettist.

737
00:57:04,971 --> 00:57:09,971
And, uh, yes, I'd like to go back to your military service, when you were in Russia.

738
00:57:09,971 --> 00:57:13,768
Yes. What kind of weapons did you have?

739
00:57:13,768 --> 00:57:17,760
Wa-weapon course or position it's called.

740
00:57:17,760 --> 00:57:22,760
(crosstalk 00:01:42) Was, were you a, were (crosstalk 00:01:43) you a little infantryman, right?

741
00:57:22,760 --> 00:57:27,760
No, I, uh, had to be there in the, at the machine gun, uh-- So

742
00:57:27,760 --> 00:57:32,760
but now I'll tell you another story about the comradeship and that's scythe.

743
00:57:32,760 --> 00:57:37,760
I was on duty, uh, New Year's Eve 1942 at night, 1942 to '43.

744
00:57:37,760 --> 00:57:41,363
And we were relieved every two hours.

745
00:57:41,363 --> 00:57:46,363
Machine gun duty, then we went back and had, we had, uh

746
00:57:46,363 --> 00:57:51,231
two big shell funnels with, uh, blankets laid out.

747
00:57:51,231 --> 00:57:54,542
That was our rest point and so on.

748
00:57:54,542 --> 00:57:59,542
And I had, uh, duty for two hours in the trench from, what we say today, twenty-two o'clock.

749
00:57:59,542 --> 00:58:03,534
Back then we said ten o'clock to midnight

750
00:58:03,534 --> 00:58:08,534
so exactly until (claps hands) the new year or the end of the year.

751
00:58:08,534 --> 00:58:13,534
And I waited for my replacement. It didn't come. Didn't come.

752
00:58:13,534 --> 00:58:18,534
I stood there for four hours until two o'clock in the morning and then finally a replacement came.

753
00:58:18,534 --> 00:58:23,013
Then I went to the back, what was at the back.

754
00:58:23,013 --> 00:58:28,013
There was half a bottle of champagne and chocolate for everyone.

755
00:58:28,013 --> 00:58:33,013
They stole everything from me. That was the camaraderie.

756
00:58:33,013 --> 00:58:38,013
When did you find out about the Holocaust? When? Mhm.

757
00:58:38,013 --> 00:58:43,013
I told you what happened to my aunts. Yes. What happened to my uncles.

758
00:58:43,013 --> 00:58:48,013
My God, I have to go again... My father went to Brazil. Uh-huh.

759
00:58:48,013 --> 00:58:53,013
My uncles-- Well, do they still have enough? Yes? Nothing left.

760
00:58:53,013 --> 00:58:58,013
(crosstalk 00:04:03) Uh, one uncle went to Shanghai. Mhm.

761
00:58:58,013 --> 00:59:02,979
The other one went to the Dominican Republic first.

762
00:59:02,979 --> 00:59:07,979
My father, as I said, went to Brazil. Mhm. Of course I knew all that. Hm.

763
00:59:07,979 --> 00:59:08,952
Of course.

764
00:59:08,952 --> 00:59:13,952
Why didn't you tell me- (crosstalk 00:04:23) The horrific events in Galicia.

765
00:59:13,952 --> 00:59:18,952
What they did to the Jewish people. Did you see that as a soldier?

766
00:59:18,952 --> 00:59:23,952
No, when I was there-- I wasn't in a section, uh, but I was in the jungle, if you like.

767
00:59:23,952 --> 00:59:28,952
We were practically in the jungle, in the so-called Demyansk cauldron. Mhm.

768
00:59:28,952 --> 00:59:33,952
Uh, that's on Lake Ilmen. The starting point was Stalaja Russa.

769
00:59:33,952 --> 00:59:38,952
There were no Jews there, there weren't any. We were practically in the forest.

770
00:59:38,952 --> 00:59:39,342
Mhm.

771
00:59:39,342 --> 00:59:44,342
Did any of your comrades know that she was a so-called (crosstalk 00:05:02) half-Jew?

772
00:59:44,342 --> 00:59:49,015
No, nope. I was also demoted. Nothing more. Mhm.

773
00:59:49,015 --> 00:59:54,015
Were you afraid that someone would find out about it?

774
00:59:54,015 --> 00:59:59,015
Oh, they wouldn't have been interested. Hmm. Really-really?

775
00:59:59,015 --> 01:00:04,015
Did, did you, when you, uh... Did you have a vacation? A what?

776
01:00:04,015 --> 01:00:09,015
When you were in the German army. Did you have a, a leave? Were you on leave?

777
01:00:09,015 --> 01:00:14,015
Yes. Never? No. Not one day while I was a soldier. Yes.

778
01:00:14,015 --> 01:00:18,787
I was on leave after every military hospital. Hm.

779
01:00:18,787 --> 01:00:23,787
And do you have other people in your family that you lost

780
01:00:23,787 --> 01:00:28,787
apart from these two aunts in the Holocaust? From the Jewish side? Mhm. No.

781
01:00:28,787 --> 01:00:33,787
So it was just the two aunts who stupidly stayed in Germany because they thought they were protected by their mother's

782
01:00:33,787 --> 01:00:38,787
uh, US citizenship. Mhm. Yes, that ended the day my grandmother closed her eyes.

783
01:00:38,787 --> 01:00:43,787
The next day, the SS came and picked up my two aunts.

784
01:00:43,787 --> 01:00:48,787
The other siblings all went and came abroad, all of them.

785
01:00:48,787 --> 01:00:53,787
And what do you think would have happened if Germany had won the war?

786
01:00:53,787 --> 01:00:58,752
What would have happened to you? We all don't know.

787
01:00:58,752 --> 01:01:01,868
We can only theorize about that.

788
01:01:01,868 --> 01:01:06,868
But we probably would have had to, uh, get off the sidewalk and, uh

789
01:01:06,868 --> 01:01:11,868
maybe we would have been sent to labor camps or whatever. Hm.

790
01:01:11,868 --> 01:01:16,868
And in Russia, did you see the Russians? Of course I did. (laughs) Hm.

791
01:01:16,868 --> 01:01:21,868
Was it difficult, uh, to shoot at other people? Oh, like where. Oh.

792
01:01:21,868 --> 01:01:26,868
We didn't, we didn't do it at all. I didn't fire a single shot in the whole war.

793
01:01:26,868 --> 01:01:31,868
But you were a machine gunner, yes? Yes. I didn't need to be.

794
01:01:31,868 --> 01:01:36,868
So, how did you - that, I would only have set it in motion if they had launched an assault.

795
01:01:36,868 --> 01:01:41,868
But they were just as happy in the trenches as we were. Hm.

796
01:01:41,868 --> 01:01:46,868
And what was your worst memory as a soldier in Russia? Pff. Worst memory? Mhm.

797
01:01:46,868 --> 01:01:51,868
Jo. That we couldn't clear out. Hm. You realize I'm getting ironic now.

798
01:01:51,868 --> 01:01:56,868
That's obvious. And you know what clearing is. There you go.

799
01:01:56,868 --> 01:02:01,868
And from all your experiences, what have you learned for your life?

800
01:02:01,868 --> 01:02:05,179
From back then? I have to tell you

801
01:02:05,179 --> 01:02:10,179
I told you earlier: I was already very independent as a boy and I didn't need to learn more.

802
01:02:10,179 --> 01:02:12,418
I just observed it all.

803
01:02:12,418 --> 01:02:17,418
I saw myself like an outsider and I still see myself today.

804
01:02:17,418 --> 01:02:22,418
I am happy that I have two wives - my first wife died - that I have this angel here.

805
01:02:22,418 --> 01:02:25,144
But we both limit ourselves.

806
01:02:25,144 --> 01:02:30,144
We live very secluded lives and I hope for a very, very long time. And, uh

807
01:02:30,144 --> 01:02:35,144
but you've probably gathered from a lot of this that I'm still involved in, uh

808
01:02:35,144 --> 01:02:39,526
politics, in the events of the day, but again

809
01:02:39,526 --> 01:02:43,908
just like an outsider watching a movie go by.

810
01:02:43,908 --> 01:02:47,900
Of course I take a stand for myself. Mmm.

811
01:02:47,900 --> 01:02:52,900
And you and I have always agreed on everything, including politics.

812
01:02:52,900 --> 01:02:57,900
We don't need anyone. We watch it, take a stand. Off.

813
01:02:57,900 --> 01:03:02,900
I don't know if you can see what's there. Do you know that? Say it again?

814
01:03:02,900 --> 01:03:07,900
The song you said on Yom Kippur. That was too long ago. Yes. So...

815
01:03:07,900 --> 01:03:12,900
But can you, uh, say that, uh, prayer for, uh, again, what you sang a little bit?

816
01:03:12,900 --> 01:03:17,900
That was nice. Well, at the beginning? Mhm. (sings) Lehu adanoj elohenu.

817
01:03:17,900 --> 01:03:20,821
(sings) Jischnah-- uh, uh, uh.

818
01:03:20,821 --> 01:03:25,821
Jischnaseh, lehu alehu, jischnas, jischnah, chis, ah, they're all gone.

819
01:03:25,821 --> 01:03:30,821
(sings) Lehu adanaj elohim. That's how we started the New Year, I think.

820
01:03:30,821 --> 01:03:35,821
That was the beginning of- Rosh Hashana? Of the N-- Yes, Rosh Hashana.

821
01:03:35,821 --> 01:03:40,821
(sings) Lehu adanaj elohenu. But that's all I know about it now. And the Shma?

822
01:03:40,821 --> 01:03:45,821
Do you still remember? Shma yisroe, yes, I remember that too.

823
01:03:45,821 --> 01:03:49,229
But, uh, it was learned, wasn't it?

824
01:03:49,229 --> 01:03:54,229
Only because I sang it very often, er, on holidays, my brother and I, it stuck a bit.

825
01:03:54,229 --> 01:03:59,229
But it was always very nice and... They were, they were comrades. And the women.

826
01:03:59,229 --> 01:04:04,229
We used to fool around in the synagogue. We were always behind laurel trees.

827
01:04:04,229 --> 01:04:09,229
Mmm. My God. There was a Berlin, uh, margarine representative who was laughing.

828
01:04:09,229 --> 01:04:14,229
He said: "I can't sing that if, if, if, if, if I'm hungry.

829
01:04:14,229 --> 01:04:19,229
I have to acheln." Right? That was all. They were all very nice.

830
01:04:19,229 --> 01:04:24,229
Do you, uh, yes, do you, uh, believe in God, do you? Do I believe in God? Yes.

831
01:04:24,229 --> 01:04:28,416
I believe in my wife. Hm. If you like. Mhm.

832
01:04:28,416 --> 01:04:33,284
And musically, it's, uh, Gustav Mahler for me. Hm.

833
01:04:33,284 --> 01:04:38,284
And do you have these, uh, songs and also, uh, these prayers, they say? Yes.

834
01:04:38,284 --> 01:04:43,284
Did you, when you experienced difficulties late in the Third Reich?

835
01:04:43,284 --> 01:04:48,284
Did you think about these songs and- No. prayers? No, no, no.

836
01:04:48,284 --> 01:04:52,763
Did you say the Shma in Russia? No, never. No.

837
01:04:52,763 --> 01:04:57,631
You know, the struggle for existence, for survival

838
01:04:57,631 --> 01:05:02,631
was the only thing that clung to your consciousness. Nothing.

839
01:05:02,631 --> 01:05:07,631
Not thinking left and right, not looking left and right, but holding on to survival, man.

840
01:05:07,631 --> 01:05:12,631
Yes? Can you imagine that? Not being able to wash your hands for eight weeks?

841
01:05:12,631 --> 01:05:17,631
No toilet? Only snow? Well. And what did you eat? Cold rations.

842
01:05:17,631 --> 01:05:22,631
But not, uh-- When we were under fire, the assholes didn't even dare to come to us.

843
01:05:22,631 --> 01:05:27,631
We had to wait until the next day for the rations to arrive and all that.

844
01:05:27,631 --> 01:05:32,631
We were all given this so-called rubber sausage. That was a hunting sausage.

845
01:05:32,631 --> 01:05:37,631
And, uh, yes, what else did we get? Oh, some canned meat. All cold.

846
01:05:37,631 --> 01:05:40,358
Never a hot meal. Only cold.

847
01:05:40,358 --> 01:05:45,358
And chocolate cola to keep us brave and, and, and, uh, cognac.

848
01:05:45,358 --> 01:05:50,358
But not in quantities, of course. Mmm. And where did you sleep?

849
01:05:50,358 --> 01:05:55,358
Yes, in the-- I told you earlier, in the grenade funnel.

850
01:05:55,358 --> 01:06:00,358
We had lined it with blankets. Mhm. And was it possible to sleep there?

851
01:06:00,358 --> 01:06:05,358
Of course it was. You wouldn't believe what a person can go through.

852
01:06:05,358 --> 01:06:10,358
Young, above all, healthy. Yes. (sings) Oh, where is she? Howo? It hurts.

853
01:06:10,358 --> 01:06:15,129
It hurts. Uh. Oh, God. Well, something like that.

854
01:06:15,129 --> 01:06:20,129
(laughs) El hoo adonai, Elohenu. Yes. (laughs) Oh, just please, go on.

855
01:06:20,129 --> 01:06:25,129
No, no, no. That's all right. I've had enough now. But I'm glad you found this.

856
01:06:25,129 --> 01:06:30,129
You know the-- Shall I tell you? Yes, briefly. Yes, a quick question, yes.

857
01:06:30,129 --> 01:06:35,129
What's your name? Can you say your name? My name is Peter Wilhelm Tescher.

858
01:06:35,129 --> 01:06:40,129
Just a moment. What is your father's name? My father's name was Wilhelm Tescher.

859
01:06:40,129 --> 01:06:45,129
And how did you find out about your Jewish ancestry? How did I find out?

860
01:06:45,129 --> 01:06:50,129
Actually, um, from my father's stories, um, which had a lot to do with his time as a soldier.

861
01:06:50,129 --> 01:06:55,129
And I held a piece of paper in my hand when I was relatively young.

862
01:06:55,129 --> 01:07:00,129
It was this key experience where it said that my father was allowed to become an officer with a special permit from Adolf Hitler.

863
01:07:00,129 --> 01:07:05,129
And, um - it was just a permit? It was a special permit. But not a license.

864
01:07:05,129 --> 01:07:10,129
No, no. No, no. Just a permit. It said, I can give you a copy of it again.

865
01:07:10,129 --> 01:07:15,129
Maybe we'll just make a list of the things I bring over to you.

866
01:07:15,129 --> 01:07:20,129
Um, it says on it that I reserve the right to make a final decision after the war.

867
01:07:20,129 --> 01:07:25,129
Hm. That's one story, the other story-- of course we asked: Why was that?

868
01:07:25,129 --> 01:07:30,129
And the other story is that during the war my father went to Bialystok

869
01:07:30,129 --> 01:07:34,510
which was occupied by the Germans at the time

870
01:07:34,510 --> 01:07:39,510
and tried to get an official certificate stating that only one of his parents

871
01:07:39,510 --> 01:07:44,510
his mother, i.e. his maternal grandparent, was of Jewish descent.

872
01:07:44,510 --> 01:07:49,510
There were no more documents about this and he actually came back with this certificate from an official from this administration.

873
01:07:49,510 --> 01:07:54,510
And that, uh, was then also, yes half a life insurance policy for my grandmother

874
01:07:54,510 --> 01:07:59,510
who- So actually both grandparents were Jewish? I don't know...

875
01:07:59,510 --> 01:08:03,697
Well, the certificate says only one parent.

876
01:08:03,697 --> 01:08:08,697
But what did your father say about that? Uh, he was, um...

877
01:08:08,697 --> 01:08:12,689
He probably didn't know himself that-- Uh

878
01:08:12,689 --> 01:08:16,876
the story is that after the First World War

879
01:08:16,876 --> 01:08:21,355
my grandfather was also called Wilhelm Tescher

880
01:08:21,355 --> 01:08:26,355
after the First World War in 1917, after the Peace of Brest-Litovsk, uh

881
01:08:26,355 --> 01:08:31,355
administrator of a large sawmill of the German army administration-- What was his name?

882
01:08:31,355 --> 01:08:36,355
Wilhelm Tescher too, yes. Also. First World War, yes

883
01:08:36,355 --> 01:08:41,355
he was the manager of a large sawmill belonging to the German army administration in the

884
01:08:41,355 --> 01:08:46,355
uh, in the then, uh, German-occupied territories near Bialystok.

885
01:08:46,355 --> 01:08:51,355
And in the nineteen hundreds - I think they had to leave there in 1919 after the capitulation.

886
01:08:51,355 --> 01:08:56,355
And then, right? And he brought a young woman with him from there.

887
01:08:56,355 --> 01:08:58,692
That was my grandmother.

888
01:08:58,692 --> 01:09:03,692
Her name was, um, Frida Sobonitzky, she was Russian of German descent and nineteen years old.

889
01:09:03,692 --> 01:09:08,692
My grandfather was thirty-nine and my father the first-born son of this marriage

890
01:09:08,692 --> 01:09:12,879
was born in Germany at the age of nineteen.

891
01:09:12,879 --> 01:09:17,879
And my grandfather then took over my parents' small sawmill, a very small sawmill.

892
01:09:17,879 --> 01:09:22,879
And this, uh, sawmill continued to run. My grandmother was here.

893
01:09:22,879 --> 01:09:27,879
There was contact with the family in Russia until the nineteen hundreds

894
01:09:27,879 --> 01:09:32,879
until the early thirties, and then Stalin resettled everyone.

895
01:09:32,879 --> 01:09:37,879
And since then there has been no sign of life from this part of the family.

896
01:09:37,879 --> 01:09:41,189
Well, actually, it's not known, uh

897
01:09:41,189 --> 01:09:46,189
that another brother of my grandmother was in Berlin again around nineteen thirties

898
01:09:46,189 --> 01:09:51,189
as far as I've been told, and met with, with, with relatives, yes.

899
01:09:51,189 --> 01:09:56,189
But there's no longer any connection to this, to these grandparents, to these relatives.

900
01:09:56,189 --> 01:10:01,189
Uh, the grandmother was there too and didn't see that as a problem with us.

901
01:10:01,189 --> 01:10:06,189
And with the seizure of power came difficulties for my father.

902
01:10:06,189 --> 01:10:10,279
He wasn't allowed to get married to Wedern

903
01:10:10,279 --> 01:10:15,279
he wasn't allowed to-- There were also difficulties with school.

904
01:10:15,279 --> 01:10:20,245
He then changed schools and couldn't do his Abitur.

905
01:10:20,245 --> 01:10:25,245
Hm.quarry with us, which incidentally was built in the Westwall.

906
01:10:25,245 --> 01:10:30,245
If the Jewish grandmother, she was born... You can look that up.

907
01:10:30,245 --> 01:10:35,245
We have a proof of ancestry, but I don't have it with me now. I can also...

908
01:10:35,245 --> 01:10:40,245
I'll write down what I... Or is she writing? Yes, I'll write it down.

909
01:10:40,245 --> 01:10:43,166
So that I can give you this...

910
01:10:43,166 --> 01:10:48,166
Yes, every document is very important if you have a lot of documents out there.

911
01:10:48,166 --> 01:10:53,166
Yes. Well, that would be the proof of ancestry, I have that somewhere.

912
01:10:53,166 --> 01:10:57,060
The authorization. Yes, so this history.

913
01:10:57,060 --> 01:11:02,060
And my grandmother isn't in any danger, at least not for the time being

914
01:11:02,060 --> 01:11:05,566
because my family is very respected.

915
01:11:05,566 --> 01:11:10,566
Although in a neighboring village a whole bunch of Jews got away

916
01:11:10,566 --> 01:11:15,566
but my grandmother, that was somewhere, that's how it was.

917
01:11:15,566 --> 01:11:20,566
There were no problems. Only my father had some problems.

918
01:11:20,566 --> 01:11:25,566
My father then became a soldier in 1939, took part in the French campaign

919
01:11:25,566 --> 01:11:30,566
in the first attacks, and after the French campaign he rejoined the pioneers.

920
01:11:30,566 --> 01:11:34,947
He had huge casualties in the first few days.

921
01:11:34,947 --> 01:11:38,550
He was with the first river pioneers.

922
01:11:38,550 --> 01:11:43,550
Then he came back to Mainz in the Galisodes and later, after the coal addiction...

923
01:11:43,550 --> 01:11:48,418
This is now a Mr. Hossen. Am I in the right place?

924
01:11:48,418 --> 01:11:53,418
I'm in the right place, right? Yes, yes. I have... Mr.

925
01:11:53,418 --> 01:11:58,418
Brosset, Lieutenant Janzen. I just want to put something here for Mrs. Schümmer.

926
01:11:58,418 --> 01:12:03,418
Here you are. I was looking for you. You were at emart. Don't worry.

927
01:12:03,418 --> 01:12:08,418
My father went with me to Russia when they went out.

928
01:12:08,418 --> 01:12:13,418
He was always in the front line and also received forty-two German Gold.

929
01:12:13,418 --> 01:12:16,047
And what did he get it for?

930
01:12:16,047 --> 01:12:21,047
We didn't talk much about direct war-related measures.

931
01:12:21,047 --> 01:12:26,047
I only know that my father led the remnants of a pioneer battalion out of the fighting for weeks

932
01:12:26,047 --> 01:12:31,047
or at least for days, as an Obergfreiter at the time and, among other things

933
01:12:31,047 --> 01:12:36,047
I believe, in connection with a serious injury to his commander.

934
01:12:36,047 --> 01:12:41,047
He's still alive, by the way. I can give you his name.

935
01:12:41,047 --> 01:12:45,137
Maybe you should talk to him on the phone.

936
01:12:45,137 --> 01:12:50,137
He was his commander for many years afterwards. That's Schmischkel.

937
01:12:50,137 --> 01:12:54,713
I think he was also a colonel, or I don't know.

938
01:12:54,713 --> 01:12:59,713
So Schmichkel, Helmut Schmichkel. And I'll write it down for you, the address.

939
01:12:59,713 --> 01:13:04,713
And did her sibling, Father, also get permission from Hinter? No.

940
01:13:04,713 --> 01:13:09,713
So there were two sisters and a brother and the brother was also a soldier.

941
01:13:09,713 --> 01:13:13,997
What was the brother's name? Fritz Brescher.

942
01:13:13,997 --> 01:13:18,997
Lives in Kloster Reichenbach near Freudenstadt here at Vogelherd.

943
01:13:18,997 --> 01:13:23,997
If he can't be reached there, he can be contacted via the Tröscher and Beilharz company.

944
01:13:23,997 --> 01:13:27,795
But we can organize that somehow later.

945
01:13:27,795 --> 01:13:32,795
As far as I know, Franz Tröscher was a prisoner for a long time.

946
01:13:32,795 --> 01:13:37,795
He had probably become a sergeant, a paymaster or something.

947
01:13:37,795 --> 01:13:42,795
I think the Russians kept the paymasters for a long time.

948
01:13:42,795 --> 01:13:47,795
Somehow he only came back from captivity at the beginning of the fifties.

949
01:13:47,795 --> 01:13:52,795
And then he took over the sawmill at home and is now also a timber merchant here in Freudenstadt.

950
01:13:52,795 --> 01:13:57,761
Yes, and my father then... Then he was suggested...

951
01:13:57,761 --> 01:14:02,761
So his superiors tried to get him to become an officer.

952
01:14:02,761 --> 01:14:05,974
And then, on the one hand... Well

953
01:14:05,974 --> 01:14:10,974
I don't remember exactly whether this certificate from Bialostock was needed at home to protect my grandmother or rather so that he could do an officer's course.

954
01:14:10,974 --> 01:14:15,974
In any case, with this special permit from Hitler, which I just...

955
01:14:15,974 --> 01:14:18,311
These are simpler files.

956
01:14:18,311 --> 01:14:23,311
So it only says Hitler, but it was actually decided by Hitler himself

957
01:14:23,311 --> 01:14:28,311
he was able to attend the officers' course in Dessau, completed this course

958
01:14:28,311 --> 01:14:32,497
as far as I know, as the best of the course

959
01:14:32,497 --> 01:14:37,497
then also experienced Hitler up close for the first time at the end

960
01:14:37,497 --> 01:14:42,497
at the end of this course, because Hitler himself passed this course, in 1943.

961
01:14:42,497 --> 01:14:47,497
Really? Yes, he went to Dessau, flew and said goodbye to this course.

962
01:14:47,497 --> 01:14:51,100
That was the last, probably the last.

963
01:14:51,100 --> 01:14:56,100
And then after a relatively short time he probably became a lieutenant and was then transferred from Russia to Italy and was back on the Russian front in the last days of the war.

964
01:14:56,100 --> 01:15:01,100
But we didn't actually talk that much about the war itself.

965
01:15:01,100 --> 01:15:04,508
It was more of a fundamental thing.

966
01:15:04,508 --> 01:15:09,508
And as a first lieutenant in the American, but then British...

967
01:15:09,508 --> 01:15:14,508
I think the Americans did it in England or something

968
01:15:14,508 --> 01:15:19,508
so he was an English prisoner and then - he was back home very early

969
01:15:19,508 --> 01:15:22,040
was of course unencumbered

970
01:15:22,040 --> 01:15:27,040
he actually came out as a convinced pacifist after the crisis

971
01:15:27,040 --> 01:15:29,474
but he was also a realist

972
01:15:29,474 --> 01:15:34,474
he first rebuilt the sawmill and then joined the KPD back then

973
01:15:34,474 --> 01:15:36,519
so he was a communist

974
01:15:36,519 --> 01:15:41,519
and after a relatively short time he took over the mayor's post in our town on a temporary basis and then

975
01:15:41,519 --> 01:15:44,926
at the age of twenty-eight, in 1948

976
01:15:44,926 --> 01:15:49,926
he was also elected mayor of the municipality or district.

977
01:15:49,926 --> 01:15:53,140
That was his entry into politics.

978
01:15:53,140 --> 01:15:58,140
Then he was fifty-five in the state parliament, fifty-seven in the Bundestag

979
01:15:58,140 --> 01:16:03,140
the European Parliament, and then, well, he became Federal Chancellor.

980
01:16:03,140 --> 01:16:08,140
And was your father proud of this German cross and gold?

981
01:16:08,140 --> 01:16:13,140
Uh, I think my father was everywhere he was in his life, he tried to make the best of it.

982
01:16:13,140 --> 01:16:18,140
I think he was, yes, I think he was someone who, you know, with everyone.

983
01:16:18,140 --> 01:16:23,140
He was always very much, very gladly and very quickly responsible for other people.

984
01:16:23,140 --> 01:16:27,229
And that is of course also in the long war

985
01:16:27,229 --> 01:16:32,229
regardless of whether you think he was unjust or just, um

986
01:16:32,229 --> 01:16:37,195
it's an ability that comes through very quickly. So

987
01:16:37,195 --> 01:16:42,195
he was a leader in every respect and I believe that this bravery was not something that was purely personal

988
01:16:42,195 --> 01:16:43,947
yes, to gain honor

989
01:16:43,947 --> 01:16:48,947
but that in this situation he also took matters into his own hands for others and

990
01:16:48,947 --> 01:16:51,187
of course, for himself.

991
01:16:51,187 --> 01:16:56,187
Yes, I believe that he tackled everything in his life with great courage.

992
01:16:56,187 --> 01:16:58,913
And it's hard to judge that.

993
01:16:58,913 --> 01:17:03,913
I myself was a soldier in the Bundeswehr, er, in peacetime.

994
01:17:03,913 --> 01:17:08,913
And it's very difficult to judge, um, how this situation, this war

995
01:17:08,913 --> 01:17:13,913
is always progressing, that your friend the pioneers, yes, a lot

996
01:17:13,913 --> 01:17:18,913
have had a lot of losses, how that affects your attitude to life.

997
01:17:18,913 --> 01:17:23,913
So you always had the feeling that he dealt with danger very calmly.

998
01:17:23,913 --> 01:17:28,913
Even afterwards, I have to say, with the threat that he knew, um, his own

999
01:17:28,913 --> 01:17:33,913
his own difficult life situation, uh, no situation at all.

1000
01:17:33,913 --> 01:17:38,913
He worked until the end and then died in Hamburg at an SPD party conference shortly before he was due to give a speech.

1001
01:17:38,913 --> 01:17:43,913
(sighs) Yes, so it's, it's changed a lot, this, this wartime.

1002
01:17:43,913 --> 01:17:48,879
I think he once wrote, perhaps I can also find this

1003
01:17:48,879 --> 01:17:52,190
that it was only in this situation

1004
01:17:52,190 --> 01:17:56,961
in which he experienced Hitler so closely in 1943

1005
01:17:56,961 --> 01:18:01,961
that he knew from that moment on that this man was crazy

1006
01:18:01,961 --> 01:18:06,732
that this man was a madman and that a catastrophe

1007
01:18:06,732 --> 01:18:10,334
which one certainly already suspected

1008
01:18:10,334 --> 01:18:15,334
but from that moment on he probably knew that this catastrophe could no longer

1009
01:18:15,334 --> 01:18:20,334
could no longer be contained. So, what did he think about his permit?

1010
01:18:20,334 --> 01:18:25,334
(sighs) Well, signed by Hitler, the mercy of the Führer.

1011
01:18:25,334 --> 01:18:30,334
So I don't think that my father, that my father's Jewish origins played a role.

1012
01:18:30,334 --> 01:18:35,334
My father was always a citizen of the world, even as a young man, when I didn't yet know him.

1013
01:18:35,334 --> 01:18:40,334
Even as a secondary school pupil, he read English and French newspapers

1014
01:18:40,334 --> 01:18:43,840
spoke five or six languages fluently

1015
01:18:43,840 --> 01:18:48,840
tried to learn a bit of Russian through these relatives

1016
01:18:48,840 --> 01:18:53,840
but I don't think that this idea of being Jewish played any role at all.

1017
01:18:53,840 --> 01:18:58,611
Uh, that, well, I don't think so. Did you... Yes.

1018
01:18:58,611 --> 01:19:03,611
Yes, did you lose any relatives in the Holocaust? No. Well, not in Germany.

1019
01:19:03,611 --> 01:19:08,090
My grandmother was the only one who came over.

1020
01:19:08,090 --> 01:19:13,090
We certainly lost relatives, but we don't know that, through Stalin's deportation.

1021
01:19:13,090 --> 01:19:18,090
Mmm. Yes. So in that respect, we're not, we're certainly not the typical, uh

1022
01:19:18,090 --> 01:19:23,055
family that lived in Germany with Jewish relatives.

1023
01:19:23,055 --> 01:19:27,242
It was just my grandmother, who was also...

1024
01:19:27,242 --> 01:19:32,242
The authorities didn't want to know exactly whether she was of half or quarter or full Jewish descent.

1025
01:19:32,242 --> 01:19:32,632
Mhm.

1026
01:19:32,632 --> 01:19:37,632
That-- But my uncle, who lived through that time, can probably tell you a lot more about that.

1027
01:19:37,632 --> 01:19:42,632
(crosstalk 00:04:48) And your father's friend, who wrote to me

1028
01:19:42,632 --> 01:19:47,632
said that your father said that his Jewish grandmother was completely Jewish.

1029
01:19:47,632 --> 01:19:52,632
It could be, it could be. Well, we didn't really talk much about that.

1030
01:19:52,632 --> 01:19:57,632
Uh, about-- you, well, it didn't really matter to us whether she was completely...

1031
01:19:57,632 --> 01:20:02,632
It was important that he got this certificate, but for us, uh, it's

1032
01:20:02,632 --> 01:20:07,632
and that's the same for us today, so, we're, um-our country.

1033
01:20:07,632 --> 01:20:12,632
We are aware of that. We've always been a country where cultures have mixed.

1034
01:20:12,632 --> 01:20:17,632
Where we come from, Roman influences are still very much in evidence.

1035
01:20:17,632 --> 01:20:22,632
And the progenitor, the first thresher, can be traced back to the Thirty Years' War.

1036
01:20:22,632 --> 01:20:27,632
I'll come back to that, also with genealogical research

1037
01:20:27,632 --> 01:20:32,632
he was a Swedish mercenary who came to Germany with Gustav Adolf and then got stuck with us

1038
01:20:32,632 --> 01:20:36,137
so he married an impostor. So for us

1039
01:20:36,137 --> 01:20:41,137
I would say that having Jewish ancestors is neither something to do with pride nor something to do with shame.

1040
01:20:41,137 --> 01:20:46,137
It's something that actually comes quite naturally to us.

1041
01:20:46,137 --> 01:20:51,137
We are six siblings and I think we all feel that way and yes

1042
01:20:51,137 --> 01:20:56,137
that's what I can actually tell you now. Doing something for people.

1043
01:20:56,137 --> 01:21:01,137
I also don't believe that he committed any atrocities without need or anything.

1044
01:21:01,137 --> 01:21:04,545
He was actually too human for that.

1045
01:21:04,545 --> 01:21:09,545
But war is an exceptional situation and I can't imagine it for someone who isn't war-minded.

1046
01:21:09,545 --> 01:21:13,148
You probably feel the same way. I do.

1047
01:21:13,148 --> 01:21:18,148
It's a situation that you only really know if you've experienced it.

1048
01:21:18,148 --> 01:21:22,334
Did he learn about the Holocaust back then?

1049
01:21:22,334 --> 01:21:27,334
I assume that at least from 1943 onwards, 44 would have been aware of some things there too.

1050
01:21:27,334 --> 01:21:32,334
I assume that. But. Difficult. Difficult to say. Did he talk about it?

1051
01:21:32,334 --> 01:21:35,548
He actually only talked about it.

1052
01:21:35,548 --> 01:21:40,548
After the war, he was always very consciously against.

1053
01:21:40,548 --> 01:21:45,548
For example, as state chairman of the SPD, which he was a strong voice

1054
01:21:45,548 --> 01:21:50,548
he chaired the parliamentary group in the state parliament.

1055
01:21:50,548 --> 01:21:55,548
In Mainz, he did not attend American receptions during the Vietnam War

1056
01:21:55,548 --> 01:22:00,548
which he considered to be an unjust war, which was a huge scandal.

1057
01:22:00,548 --> 01:22:05,548
So he had a lot of self-confidence and moral courage when he thought that injustice was being done.

1058
01:22:05,548 --> 01:22:10,548
And then he did. He didn't stand up for himself, he didn't do it.

1059
01:22:10,548 --> 01:22:15,548
He didn't go there and he wrote to them to explain why he wasn't coming.

1060
01:22:15,548 --> 01:22:20,221
And that's in a state like Rhineland-Palatinate.

1061
01:22:20,221 --> 01:22:25,221
There was a huge uproar and scandal that someone didn't go to see his American friends.

1062
01:22:25,221 --> 01:22:30,221
He did things like that. He was affected by these experiences after the war.

1063
01:22:30,221 --> 01:22:35,221
I think it was more of a reinforcement or an imprint on his personality

1064
01:22:35,221 --> 01:22:38,629
which then developed after the war.

1065
01:22:38,629 --> 01:22:43,629
I was born shortly after the war and I witnessed a lot of people who then expressed themselves in such a way that he really fought very

1066
01:22:43,629 --> 01:22:48,629
very hard for peace, for justice, for social justice, for development

1067
01:22:48,629 --> 01:22:52,621
for international understanding and so on

1068
01:22:52,621 --> 01:22:57,621
that we can actually talk about very personal experiences in the war

1069
01:22:57,621 --> 01:23:02,621
which I'm sure we did. You can't survive a war like that without feeling guilty.

1070
01:23:02,621 --> 01:23:07,621
I don't think that's possible. But we never really talked about that.

1071
01:23:07,621 --> 01:23:12,621
I believe that his personality was shaped by these experiences

1072
01:23:12,621 --> 01:23:16,711
which he ultimately classified as terrible

1073
01:23:16,711 --> 01:23:21,711
but which he faced up to as the person he was by trying to become a hero. Yes.

1074
01:23:21,711 --> 01:23:26,711
They didn't come about because he somehow only ever stood up for a just cause

1075
01:23:26,711 --> 01:23:31,711
but because you make decisions and take things into your own hands in situations where your own life and the lives of your comrades are at stake.

1076
01:23:31,711 --> 01:23:36,711
And I assume that it was more this imprint that played a role later on

1077
01:23:36,711 --> 01:23:41,711
which was the sum of the experiences during the war.

1078
01:23:41,711 --> 01:23:46,711
There is a brochure from the political period that also contains a bit about the war.

1079
01:23:46,711 --> 01:23:51,711
I will enclose it when I send it to you. Before we talk about your list.

1080
01:23:51,711 --> 01:23:56,711
Can you tell me your name? What is your name? Friedrich Christian Stahl.

1081
01:23:56,711 --> 01:24:01,579
When were you born? On October 28, 1918 in Berlin.

1082
01:24:01,579 --> 01:24:05,669
And you talked about Labram a bit earlier.

1083
01:24:05,669 --> 01:24:10,669
How did you know that Heinrich Labram had experienced so many problems?

1084
01:24:10,669 --> 01:24:12,811
We were both together.

1085
01:24:12,811 --> 01:24:17,811
We were both heads of department at the Military History Research Office

1086
01:24:17,811 --> 01:24:22,811
so we often spoke to each other and also socialized with each other.

1087
01:24:22,811 --> 01:24:27,811
And what did he say about his experience in the Kriegsmarine?

1088
01:24:27,811 --> 01:24:32,811
Paraprophe came out and the Jewish officers who had not taken part in the First World War were to be excluded from the Wehrmacht.

1089
01:24:32,811 --> 01:24:33,882
In his case

1090
01:24:33,882 --> 01:24:38,882
it was particularly tragic because his brother had already crashed after 1933 or in 1933 as a trained aviation officer.

1091
01:24:38,882 --> 01:24:43,882
When the question came to him, he himself asked to speak to his high commander, Admiral Raeder.

1092
01:24:43,882 --> 01:24:48,653
He was refused. And he was very angry about that.

1093
01:24:48,653 --> 01:24:53,653
After the war, did he try to have a court case with ??? did he?

1094
01:24:53,653 --> 01:24:58,619
I don't think so. He didn't talk about that either.

1095
01:24:58,619 --> 01:25:03,619
I think we've finished the Lebram case. Then I spoke about Österreicher.

1096
01:25:03,619 --> 01:25:08,619
Österreicher was a lieutenant in motorized division seven, which was in Munich.

1097
01:25:08,619 --> 01:25:13,390
And- From the first name, you know? I don't know.

1098
01:25:13,390 --> 01:25:18,390
You know, the first name never played a role in the German army.

1099
01:25:18,390 --> 01:25:23,390
Or let's say in the Prussian, in the Bavarian, yes. Okay.

1100
01:25:23,390 --> 01:25:28,390
(Laughter) I only know the case and I know that Österreicher survived the war.

1101
01:25:28,390 --> 01:25:33,390
Hm. That's all I can say. And he had been with your father?

1102
01:25:33,390 --> 01:25:38,390
How did you know that he was an officer candidate with my father, i.e.

1103
01:25:38,390 --> 01:25:43,356
as an ensign and midshipman at the infantry school.

1104
01:25:43,356 --> 01:25:48,029
My father was a teacher for the midshipmen, i.e.

1105
01:25:48,029 --> 01:25:52,314
for the second course at the infantry school

1106
01:25:52,314 --> 01:25:57,314
and that's how I got to know all of them - there were only ten of them for the motorized troops

1107
01:25:57,314 --> 01:26:01,598
for example. And what was going on with him?

1108
01:26:01,598 --> 01:26:06,598
Did he have a Jewish parent or big ones? I don't know that.

1109
01:26:06,598 --> 01:26:11,598
I only knew him until he was nineteen thirty-one or thirty-two and not after that.

1110
01:26:11,598 --> 01:26:16,598
And ah yes, was, did he get a declaration of German blood?

1111
01:26:16,598 --> 01:26:21,598
How was it possible that he stayed in the German Wehrmacht?

1112
01:26:21,598 --> 01:26:26,598
No, no, he didn't get a declaration of German blood, because he had to leave.

1113
01:26:26,598 --> 01:26:31,077
So he was discharged first? Yes. The next one?

1114
01:26:31,077 --> 01:26:36,077
Yes, then there are some cases where I just want to say the name.

1115
01:26:36,077 --> 01:26:41,077
I'm sure you're familiar with these cases. I've already said Backenköhler. Mhm.

1116
01:26:41,077 --> 01:26:46,077
You will of course be familiar with Wilberg. Milk. And Backenköhler.

1117
01:26:46,077 --> 01:26:51,077
You have an interesting story about the naval adjutant.

1118
01:26:51,077 --> 01:26:56,077
I remember that either Raeder's adjutant or a personnel officer or the head of the naval personnel office came to Raeder and drew his attention to the order that naval officers of Jewish descent had to be dismissed.

1119
01:26:56,077 --> 01:26:59,095
And Raeder is said to have said

1120
01:26:59,095 --> 01:27:04,095
"That doesn't concern the navy." To which the man in question replied, "But Mr.

1121
01:27:04,095 --> 01:27:09,095
Admiral," and mentioned several names, including Backenköhler. Hm.

1122
01:27:09,095 --> 01:27:12,211
I can't say any more about that.

1123
01:27:12,211 --> 01:27:17,211
It was all a very long time ago that I heard that and I don't remember who said it.

1124
01:27:17,211 --> 01:27:22,211
Mhm. Then there was the case of General Kühntal, military attaché in Paris.

1125
01:27:22,211 --> 01:27:26,300
Kühlintal? Kühlintal, yes. Ah The admiral?

1126
01:27:26,300 --> 01:27:31,300
The admiral is, if I'm not mistaken, a brother of his. I see.

1127
01:27:31,300 --> 01:27:36,364
Yes, he came out of the war mine in nineteen-twenty.
